"'''A Survey of Provenance Models in Open Knowledge Graphs'''" reviews the principal approaches to recording provenance in publicly available knowledge graphs, comparing their expressivity, query support, and adoption in practice. The paper argues that pragmatic, layered models tend to outperform fully expressive frameworks once real-world editorial workflows are considered.

The work informs the [[Heritage Linked Data]] programme by clarifying which provenance patterns are realistic to adopt when integrating heterogeneous cultural heritage datasets.
